‚ÄúI hope today will be truly memorable for you and you will enjoy this festival of celebration.‚Äù
‚ÄúCompassionate leadership is enabling. It captures the skills of the whole team and ensures those skills are used in the most effective way.‚Äù

‚ÄúThe pandemic has had a huge impact on levels of stress, psychological distress and burnout. I urge you to be self-aware, to be mindful of your own wellbeing.‚Äù

Training and time for training is critical to maintaining and developing the workforce. We welcome the plans for a National Workforce Strategy and view this as pivotal to the implementation of the Recovery plan.

These commitments will help to meet increasing demand; we also need to be mindful of the immediate challenges we face. Our healthcare services are facing exceptionally high levels of demand and rapidly building capacity is going to be essential as is managing public expectations

Workforce capacity can be supported through the development and training of enhanced roles such as advanced nurse practitioners and surgical care practitioners to maximise the workforce and we welcome the commitment to build on the workforce across multiple specialist areas

We welcome the commitment in the recovery plan to deliver on both of these areas over the next five years. However, these initiatives will take many years to grow our workforce and we believe it is essential that there is more focus on retention of staff.

Recruitment & retention are two of the most pressing issues facing our health service. We have frequently called for action to increase the number of medical school places to address our workforce shortage, and to widen participation to those from areas of multiple deprivation

Health and wellbeing of the workforce is critical to any recovery of services. We welcome the commitment to increase investment in staff wellbeing and support, including additional funding for rest areas, peer support, and the development of a new National Wellbeing Programme
The crisis in social care and the development of the National Care Service is also a key area that needs to be addressed to make meaningful change across the whole system.

It is essential that workforce, wellbeing of staff and innovative approaches to service re-design are key aspects of the recovery, and we are pleased to see each of these key challenges being addressed in the plan.
There are many positive initiatives in @scotgov NHS Recovery Plan to address some of the key challenges in our health service over a realistic time scale https://t.co/MFvbnfILbW

‚ÄúWe welcome the Diplomates at the Ceremony today, we look forward to working with you in the Faculty of Travel Medicine in the future, and many congratulations on your latest success.‚Äù @janechiodini

‚ÄúThe pandemic has had a significant impact on travel medicine practitioners all over the world. But when travel does open up again and we‚Äôre seeing travellers in abundance, high standards of care will never be more important.‚Äù @janechiodini, Dean, Faculty of Travel Medicine

‚ÄúIt is my pleasure to address the graduating Fellows and Members who have completed a wonderful task, having graduated to the next level of serving mankind in the future.‚Äù Guest speaker and College Fellow @ProfBhargava welcomes our newest Fellows and Members.

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs been an eventful year to say the least with COVID having a global impact on both our professional lives and indeed our personal lives. I‚Äôm very humbled when I hear the scores of stories‚Ä¶ that our profession has very much risen to the challenge posed by COVID.‚Äù @SurgeonAndy
‚ÄúIt‚Äôs an absolute pleasure and a delight to welcome you from all around the globe to our online virtual Diploma Ceremony, virtually from Glasgow.‚Äù VP (Dental) @SurgeonAndy

Miss Kirsty Cowan receives the TC White Medal for performance in the MFDS Part 2 exam from @SurgeonAndy; ‚ÄúI‚Äôm absolutely delighted to accept this award, and I‚Äôm really grateful to the College for giving me the opportunity to sit the MFDS part 2, despite the COVID19 pandemic.‚Äù
‚ÄúI am delighted you are now part of this fraternity, and I look forward to meeting you in the future.  Welcome to your College.‚Äù Professor Abhay Rane, (VP, Surgical)

‚ÄúIt is a real honour to welcome you to this Ceremony. [The College] is 400 years old, and we have a vision that remains unchanged for 400 years and that is to promote the highest standards of healthcare.‚Äù Professor Abhay Rane, (VP, Surgical)

‚ÄúI‚Äôd like to thank all the mentors and colleagues who‚Äôve taught me, spent time with me and mentored me through the years. This is a testament to the all the fantastic support I‚Äôve had across the West of Scotland in my training over the years.‚Äù @DocJimmyP83

Professor Abhay Rane (VP, Surgical) awards the Graham Teasdale Medal to @DocJimmyP83 for his performance in the FRCS Part 2 exam last year. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs an honour and a privilege to accept this award, particularly given all the stress and uncertainty around the exam with the pandemic.‚Äù

‚ÄúI‚Äôm delighted to welcome so many physician colleagues to Membership and Fellowship of the College today. I trust this will be the beginning of a long and beneficial partnership as a valued member of our College community.‚Äù College VP(Medical) @AdrianStanleyGI
‚ÄúIn the post-COVID era, we hope to be better partners and friends across the pond, as we join forces to improve standards not only for our patients, but for our members.‚Äù @mikevalentineMD

Dr Roderick Neilson introduces our third Honorary Fellow, @mikevalentineMD, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm truly grateful to be considered for Honorary Fellowship in the Royal College. Since 1599 you have stood for excellence in patient care and the standards that we must meet.‚Äù

Dr Neilson introduces our 2nd Honorary Fellow, @DickKovacs, ‚ÄúI‚Äôd like to thank the College for bestowing Honorary Fellowship on me. This year has been like no other, and while it has caused us to deal with things at great distance, in some ways it‚Äôs brought us closer together.‚Äù
‚ÄúI consider this degree as more important and more prestigious than any other degree I have ever been awarded in view of my passion for the art of surgery.‚Äù @HakimNadey

College Registrar Dr Roderick Neilson introduces the first of our Honorary Fellows; @HakimNadey, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm very proud to be here today for this special event, but I‚Äôm also humbled by the great tribute of being awarded an Honorary Fellowship.‚Äù

‚ÄúWe must remember the power of kindness. It benefits those who receive, but it also benefits those who give. We‚Äôre taught to be clear, to communicate well, to involve patients ‚Äì but let‚Äôs at all times remember to do those things with kindness and compassion.‚Äù @JackieDocjt

‚ÄúDuring the pandemic we‚Äôve all witnessed the power of acts of kindness. Food for hospital workers, care for neighbours, visits for those who are lonely, volunteers helping clinicians in hospitals.  The power of kindness is greatly underrated, but can be transformational.‚Äù
‚ÄúWhat defines us is how we respond to challenges and hurdles ‚Äì and perseverance really will get you anywhere.‚Äù
‚ÄúIt is that same spirit of perseverance which has brought you here, to be joining us today.‚Äù

‚ÄòPerseverance will get you anywhere‚Äô - @JackieDocjt quotes @NASAPersevere first tweet from the surface of Mars: ‚ÄúA really important philosophy and message. It‚Äôs that same innovation and initiative ‚Ä¶ that will get us out of COVID.‚Äù
‚ÄúWe‚Äôve also passed new regulations which will ensure that, for the first time in its 420 years, in this year‚Äôs elections our Fellows living and working outside the UK will be able to vote.‚Äù

‚ÄúAs a College, we have been looking very carefully at how we become a more fair, inclusive and transparent organisation. And this means not just having an equality and diversity policy sitting on a shelf, but actively implementing it through our Inclusion Advisory Group.‚Äù
‚ÄúThis may seem like an impossible task, but then as Mandela said, ‚Äòit always seems impossible ‚Äì until it‚Äôs done‚Äô.‚Äù

‚ÄúAs we begin to recover healthcare services around the world, it is our responsibility to ensure we focus on resolving these inequalities and that requires not a just a change to healthcare, but to the very fabric of our societies.‚Äù
‚ÄúHealth inequalities have long been evident, but we are all aware and have witnessed the disproportionate effect that coronavirus has had on different sectors of our societies.‚Äù

‚ÄúIt is often said that we‚Äôre facing the same storm together. While that is true to a point, it is also clear we are in very different boats ... COVID has shone it‚Äôs light on so many injustices and allowed us to see things through a different lens.‚Äù

‚ÄúThe global pandemic, from which we are all suffering, has been likened to a severe storm. It is a true force of nature. It is unpredictable. It is unforgiving. We‚Äôre all trying to weather that storm.‚Äù

‚ÄúWe‚Äôre very proud of our heritage, but we‚Äôre not imprisoned by it. And embracing digital technologies and new technologies in medicine are crucial to progress in medicine and surgery in general.‚Äù
‚ÄúWe‚Äôve also learned how to stay connected ‚Ä¶ As a College, it means we can be far more inclusive than ever before ‚Äì and more engaged with you, and in the moment.‚Äù

‚ÄúWe have learned so much in this past year ‚Ä¶ What is important to us? What really matters? The hope is, that will translate into our societies, re-evaluating what is important and prioritise a fairer, more caring society.‚Äù
